caption: Table 1: Comparison of the overall ZO oracle complexity of single-loop algorithms to find an e-stationary point of f (Definition 3) or ψ (Definition 2). κ = l/µ denotes the condition number, d = dx + dy and Õ(·) hides logarithmic terms. Abbreviation: Settings (Set.), Algorithms (Algs.), Regular (Reg.), Theorem (The.).
description: This table compares the overall zeroth-order (ZO) oracle complexity of different algorithms for finding an e-stationary point in solving nonconvex minimax problems.  It shows the complexity for various settings (nonconvex-concave, nonconvex-strongly concave), algorithms, and regularization choices.  The complexity is expressed in terms of the dimension (d), condition number (κ), and accuracy (ε).  It also distinguishes between deterministic and stochastic settings.

description: This table compares the overall zeroth-order (ZO) oracle complexity of different algorithms for finding an epsilon-stationary point for various settings of the minimax optimization problem.  It considers both deterministic and stochastic settings, and different regularization schemes (no regularization, indicator function regularization, and L1 regularization). The table shows the complexity in terms of the dimension (d), condition number (κ), and epsilon (ε).  The algorithms are categorized by their settings (NC, NC-SC, C, etc.) and their overall complexity is presented.
